questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;He asked me if I would like a drink&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;Steps to follow to change Direct speech to Indirect Speech :&lt;/span&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;The &lt;strong&gt;commas and inverted commas&lt;/strong&gt; are removed.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;The word&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;that&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;or&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;if&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&amp;nbsp;is put between the reporting verb and reported speech.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pronouns&lt;/strong&gt; of direct speech are changed according to their &lt;strong&gt;relation between the reporter and the&amp;nbsp;hearer&lt;/strong&gt; e.g. The first person of indirect speech changes according to the subject.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;
		&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span id=&quot;docs-internal-guid-9f53497c-7fff-73e4-36d3-68f67a88efec&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;  font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;When the reporting verb of direct speech is in past tense then all the present tenses are changed to the &lt;strong&gt;corresponding past tense&lt;/strong&gt; in indirect speech.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;
		&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;&quot;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;  font-variant-numeric: normal; font-variant-east-asian: normal; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;The words expressing &lt;strong&gt;nearness in time or places&lt;/strong&gt; of the direct speech are changed to their appropriate forms e.g. here-there, today- that day, now- then, tomorrow- next day, etc.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;white-space: pre-wrap;&quot;&gt;​&lt;/span&gt;​&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
		&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li style=&quot;line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;&quot;&gt;
	&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot; style=&quot;line-height:1.38;margin-top:0pt;margin-bottom:0pt;&quot;&gt;Following the above-mentioned steps, the &lt;strong&gt;indirect form&lt;/strong&gt; of the given sentence would be:&amp;nbsp;&lt;em&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: 700; &quot;&gt;He asked me if I would like a drink.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;The correct answer is &lt;strong&gt;&amp;#39;Change&amp;#39;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The sentence discusses that an adjustment in the weather led to the interruption of their plans.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The word &amp;#39;Change&amp;#39;, signifying the act or process of altering, fits perfectly into the sentence. Change in the weather is common and often leads to adjustments in plans.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;#39;Change&amp;#39; seamlessly blends into a description of weather, a natural phenomenon known for its fluctuating nature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It underscores the unpredictability of weather and its potential impact on human plans, thereby enhancing the realism of the sentence.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Therefore, the correct answer is &amp;#39;Change&amp;#39;.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul dir=&quot;ltr&quot;&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&amp;#39;Improvement&amp;#39;, &amp;#39;Decline&amp;#39;, or &amp;#39;Stabilization&amp;#39; of weather could potentially disrupt plans, but &amp;#39;Change&amp;#39; is more neutral and can cover all of these conditions. It is also more generally applicable, making it the best choice for this context&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

